WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

2
00:00:26.840 --> 00:00:28.640
<i>But is there water coming in?</i>

3
00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:31.720
<i>Like hell there is.</i>
<i>I'm on my way down now.</i>

4
00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:35.520
We had not had a vacation
since having a baby.

5
00:00:36.720 --> 00:00:39.520
I think I went to John and I said
this would be a really good time for us

6
00:00:39.600 --> 00:00:43.160
to do this amazing trip
that we've talked about doing for so long.

7
00:00:44.680 --> 00:00:47.280
which was a huge deal for us.

8
00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:00.560
The night of Friday 13th. I'd been
on board for four months as a dancer.

9
00:01:01.960 --> 00:01:04.840
I had no idea something was gonna happen.

10
00:01:08.640 --> 00:01:12.760
One moment. you are celebrating
and chilling with your family.

11
00:01:18.520 --> 00:01:22.160
The next moment. you're just there.

12
00:01:23.240 --> 00:01:24.120
powerless.

13
00:01:33.840 --> 00:01:39.040
It felt like
the ground under our feet opened.

14
00:01:40.640 --> 00:01:44.120
People were grabbing onto the walls
and grabbing onto each other.

15
00:01:45.280 --> 00:01:49.080
This is straight out of a scene
of <i>Titanic</i>. completely.

16
00:01:50.360 --> 00:01:54.360
<i>Stories of fear and panic</i>
<i>from the cruise ship Costa Concordia.</i>

17
00:01:54.880 --> 00:01:55.720
Let's be honest.

18
00:01:55.800 --> 00:01:59.080
you have thought about it every time
you get on a plane or a cruise ship.

19
00:01:59.160 --> 00:02:01.240
What happens if something goes wrong?

20
00:02:01.320 --> 00:02:02.480
Well. it happened.

21
00:02:04.880 --> 00:02:09.240
Every time you close your eyes.
you see something from the night.

22
00:02:11.120 --> 00:02:14.240
Just literally back in
the most terrifying moment

23
00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:16.600
you've ever experienced with your family.

24
00:02:19.680 --> 00:02:21.360
<i>God. what have I done?</i>

25
00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:35.040
We'd been to Europe before.
but never together.

26
00:02:35.560 --> 00:02:38.000
So it'd definitely be
our longest vacation together.

27
00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:39.840
our furthest vacation together.

28
00:02:39.920 --> 00:02:43.200
Our daughter. Lila. was 14 months old.

29
00:02:43.720 --> 00:02:48.640
so we felt like it was a good opportunity
for us to do a really big trip together.

30
00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:53.120
I'm pretty sure we packed
a suitcase of toys. diapers. diaper wipes.

31
00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:55.560
you know. the whole thing.
We had so much stuff.

32
00:02:56.280 --> 00:03:01.400
We were going to Paris.
Switzerland. Venice. Barcelona.

33
00:03:01.480 --> 00:03:04.000
Ultimately. we would end on a cruise ship.

34
00:03:04.840 --> 00:03:08.160
Yeah. I think that was a big part
of why we chose this vacation.

35
00:03:08.240 --> 00:03:10.720
We took endless photos and videos.

36
00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:13.040
made a ton of incredible memories.

37
00:03:15.040 --> 00:03:17.080
I always wanted to go to Italy.

38
00:03:19.120 --> 00:03:21.800
That was. like.
the highest on my bucket list.

39
00:03:22.320 --> 00:03:26.120
but I didn't really know
I was going on a cruise ship.

40
00:03:26.680 --> 00:03:30.200
I hadn't told her that part yet.
Just told her the Italy part.

41
00:03:30.280 --> 00:03:32.880
but the cruise ship was gonna be
a special surprise.

42
00:03:35.560 --> 00:03:39.920
We had been dating for about three years
at that time.

43
00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:44.160
The idea was. at some point.
I was going to ask her to marry me.

44
00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:46.160
If you ask someone to marry you.

45
00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:48.920
you'd want the most romantic place
you could find.

46
00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:52.600
and on this journey. there was
quite a few places to choose from.

47
00:03:53.920 --> 00:03:56.200
This would just be
that moment where everything clicks.

48
00:03:59.040 --> 00:04:02.120
She can't say no. right?
If you ask 'em in the perfect place?

49
00:04:02.200 --> 00:04:04.680
Everybody thinks that.
if you're gonna do it. right?

50
00:04:06.640 --> 00:04:08.000
When I arrived.

51
00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:13.440
I was amazed with how big
and enormous the ship looked.

52
00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:17.480
At the time. I was 17.

53
00:04:17.560 --> 00:04:23.000
My mother wanted to celebrate
her 50th birthday.

54
00:04:25.720 --> 00:04:28.880
She booked for me.
my boyfriend at the time.

55
00:04:28.960 --> 00:04:32.040
and her childhood best friend. Luisa.

56
00:04:33.680 --> 00:04:37.560
Since I was very little.
we did everything together.

57
00:04:38.360 --> 00:04:43.320
I was about seven years old
when she was diagnosed with cancer.

58
00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:47.840
But a few months before our departure.

59
00:04:47.920 --> 00:04:50.360
her cancer was in remission.

60
00:04:50.440 --> 00:04:55.720
This was definitely another big reason
to celebrate her birthday.

61
00:04:58.080 --> 00:05:01.920
The first thing we did
was explore the… the ship.

62
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:08.800
I knew that it was going to be
the largest ship I've ever seen.

63
00:05:09.400 --> 00:05:12.600
I still remember stepping into the ship
for the first time

64
00:05:12.680 --> 00:05:16.480
and just being overwhelmed
by how extravagant everything was.

65
00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:22.000
Very opulent. Chandeliers everywhere.

66
00:05:22.520 --> 00:05:25.920
It seemed like everything was either made
of gold or glass or marble.

67
00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:27.760
Very sort of old Italy.

68
00:05:27.840 --> 00:05:31.040
You know.
just everything shining and perfect.

69
00:05:32.960 --> 00:05:35.880
I didn't know exactly what room
I was gonna get when I booked it.

70
00:05:36.840 --> 00:05:38.760
At that time.
the trip was quite expensive.

71
00:05:38.840 --> 00:05:40.800
and I was a… a student.

72
00:05:41.440 --> 00:05:45.320
But he made sure
he got the best room that we could have.

73
00:05:49.800 --> 00:05:53.680
I was so happy because we got the balcony.
and we have this beautiful view.

74
00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:56.120
We walked on the balcony.

75
00:05:56.200 --> 00:05:58.040
and Nick pointed out.

76
00:05:58.120 --> 00:06:04.040
"Hey look. about a floor or two below us
is the lifeboats."

77
00:06:04.120 --> 00:06:06.000
The lifeboats. 

78
00:06:06.080 --> 00:06:08.400
And I thought.
"Well. I'll take a picture of that."

79
00:06:12.200 --> 00:06:14.680
I've never been on a cruise ship.

80
00:06:14.760 --> 00:06:19.320
and I thought. "Well. say if something
like the Titanic happens…"

81
00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:21.760
And I said.
"It's not gonna be like the Titanic."

82
00:06:21.840 --> 00:06:24.800
"I've been on cruises before. It's gonna
be fantastic. You're gonna love it."

83
00:06:30.160 --> 00:06:33.000
Kids. don't you dare run away from here!

84
00:06:42.280 --> 00:06:46.880
When we first got
on board. it was pretty amazing.

85
00:06:46.960 --> 00:06:48.480
We met with someone that asked us

86
00:06:48.560 --> 00:06:50.680
what we wanted to do
for the rest of the week.

87
00:06:50.760 --> 00:06:53.840
We set up a spa day.
and it just was so exciting. right?

88
00:06:53.920 --> 00:06:55.280
This was all happening so fast.

89
00:06:55.360 --> 00:06:57.520
We had just gotten to our room.
Now we're walkin' around.

90
00:06:58.040 --> 00:07:01.080
As we're walkin'.
I'm taking pictures of everything.

91
00:07:04.280 --> 00:07:06.640
One of the amazing things about cruising

92
00:07:06.720 --> 00:07:10.560
is that it's going to provide you
with everything.

93
00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:13.160
And so for me. especially as a new mom.

94
00:07:13.240 --> 00:07:15.160
that made it really easy.

95
00:07:15.240 --> 00:07:17.480
There were endless restaurants
of every type.

96
00:07:17.560 --> 00:07:20.800
you know. theaters. shows. casino.

97
00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:23.320
The only difficulty. really.
is how to spend your time

98
00:07:23.400 --> 00:07:25.320
in terms of how many choices there are.

99
00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:29.640
I remember an ice cream bar
where you could make your own sundaes.

100
00:07:29.720 --> 00:07:31.560
and I feel like it was 24 hours a day.

101
00:07:31.640 --> 00:07:33.760
you could just eat ice cream
if you wanted.

102
00:07:36.600 --> 00:07:39.280
This was back
when <i>The Walking Dead </i>was kinda big.

103
00:07:39.360 --> 00:07:40.960
and so we'd always play a game.

104
00:07:41.040 --> 00:07:43.240
You know. "If zombies attacked.
where would you go.

105
00:07:43.320 --> 00:07:46.680
and what weapon would you use
to either fight or get out?"

106
00:07:46.760 --> 00:07:49.360
Like. "Where would you go?
Would you go out that way or that way?"

107
00:07:49.440 --> 00:07:53.200
And if it's a slow zombie.
where's the weapon you can use to stop it?

108
00:07:53.280 --> 00:07:55.200
When he would do this to me.

109
00:07:55.280 --> 00:07:59.440
the first time. I told him. "I don't know.
I wasn't really paying attention."

110
00:07:59.520 --> 00:08:01.160
-And he's like. "Wrong!"
-Exactly.

111
00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:02.480
-Exactly.
-"Wrong!"

112
00:08:02.560 --> 00:08:04.040
"That's where you messed up."

113
00:08:04.120 --> 00:08:09.680
Slowly I started to really pay attention
to my surroundings.

114
00:08:11.880 --> 00:08:13.600

115
00:08:13.680 --> 00:08:16.920
The weather was clear.
a little cold because it was January.

116
00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.120
However. it was a quiet evening
like any other.

117
00:08:22.400 --> 00:08:25.400
I worked with Costa for about 43 years.

118
00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:27.720
You always work on a ship.

119
00:08:28.240 --> 00:08:32.000
Christmas. New Year's.
Easter. Saturday and Sunday.

120
00:08:33.080 --> 00:08:35.640
I felt more at home on board than at home.

121
00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:43.880
About 800 people worked for me
on the Costa Concordia.

122
00:08:45.480 --> 00:08:48.400
So by the night of Friday 13th January.

123
00:08:48.480 --> 00:08:52.440
I'd been working on board for four months
as a dancer.

124
00:08:52.520 --> 00:08:55.120
At that point.
it was absolutely my dream job.

125
00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:57.960
It was literally heaven on earth.

126
00:08:58.040 --> 00:09:01.720
Getting to explore the world.
I was in the best shape of my life.

127
00:09:01.800 --> 00:09:03.320
I had great friends.

128
00:09:03.840 --> 00:09:04.920
It was magic.

129
00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:12.440
On behalf of the management
of Costa and the entire crew.

130
00:09:12.520 --> 00:09:15.080
I am pleased and honored
to welcome you on board.

131
00:09:16.240 --> 00:09:18.400
I met Captain Schettino a few times.

132
00:09:18.480 --> 00:09:21.600
The first time I met him
was in the crew elevator.

133
00:09:21.680 --> 00:09:23.400
The only thing I kind of knew about him

134
00:09:23.480 --> 00:09:26.280
was that he was
a newer captain to this ship.

135
00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:27.680
Enjoy your cruise.

136
00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:33.320
One time. my mum came to visit on board.

137
00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:35.240
and he was talking with my mum.

138
00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:36.640
and he was saying

139
00:09:36.720 --> 00:09:39.920
that he was gonna go fishing
on the island with one of his friends

140
00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:41.200
but not to tell anyone

141
00:09:41.280 --> 00:09:43.800
because he wasn't actually allowed
to do that.

142
00:09:43.880 --> 00:09:46.040
And so there was also this. like.

143
00:09:46.120 --> 00:09:49.440
"Oh. he's working the system"
kind of thing.

144
00:09:53.120 --> 00:09:56.720
That night.
around nine. the captain calls me.

145
00:09:58.640 --> 00:10:04.120
A few days earlier.
the head waiter had asked the captain

146
00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:07.680
if the ship could do a sail-by salute
close to Giglio Island

147
00:10:07.760 --> 00:10:11.440
since both his sister and his mother
lived on the island.

148
00:10:15.480 --> 00:10:20.480
He asked me if I would like to join him
on the bridge for the sail-by.

149
00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.520
To me. it sounded a bit unusual. because.

150
00:10:25.280 --> 00:10:28.680
as it was night. all dark.
there wasn't much to see.

151
00:10:28.760 --> 00:10:31.040
But. as this was the captain's decision.

152
00:10:31.120 --> 00:10:33.560
we complied.

153
00:10:48.920 --> 00:10:51.280
That night. me and my boyfriend. Andrea.

154
00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:55.480
decided to go up on the deck of the pool.

155
00:10:56.200 --> 00:10:58.000
As I opened the door.

156
00:10:58.520 --> 00:11:01.560
I felt this fresh breeze.

157
00:11:04.560 --> 00:11:06.520
Everything was dark.

158
00:11:06.600 --> 00:11:10.040
but it was light up by the few lights.

159
00:11:11.600 --> 00:11:15.240
Sparkles just reflect on the water.

160
00:11:16.640 --> 00:11:20.000
I lean out. I was watching the sea.

161
00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:25.200
and Andrea. who was behind me.
he hugged me.

162
00:11:25.720 --> 00:11:29.320
He said. "It feels like the Titanic."

163
00:11:29.880 --> 00:11:31.920
At that moment. I…

164
00:11:32.920 --> 00:11:34.160
Actually. I…

165
00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:36.320
I felt a little strange.

166
00:11:36.840 --> 00:11:38.200
But it's crazy. right?

167
00:11:38.280 --> 00:11:44.200
So you… you just…
leave that… that thought behind.

168
00:11:45.640 --> 00:11:49.520
And then I received this call
from my mother.

169
00:11:50.160 --> 00:11:52.160
She said. "We are here in the restaurant."

170
00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:56.240
"They are beginning to serve dinner.
so please come on. join us."

171
00:11:58.800 --> 00:12:00.840
It was kind of an important dinner

172
00:12:00.920 --> 00:12:02.880
because. at midnight.

173
00:12:02.960 --> 00:12:05.240
it would be her birthday.

174
00:12:09.280 --> 00:12:11.320
That night. we had a really nice dinner.

175
00:12:11.400 --> 00:12:12.840
Can you say hi to Daddy?

176
00:12:12.920 --> 00:12:16.840
But following dinner.
with Lila being one. it was time for bed.

177
00:12:16.920 --> 00:12:18.680
We went back to the cabin
and put her down.

178
00:12:20.840 --> 00:12:23.240
We just did
our traditional bedtime routine.

179
00:12:23.320 --> 00:12:25.200
Getting on my pajamas.

180
00:12:25.280 --> 00:12:29.040
I come out of the shower.
have my boxer shorts on. getting into bed.

181
00:12:29.120 --> 00:12:30.920
And I remember laying down

182
00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:34.120
and actually verbalizing.
"I am exhausted."

183
00:12:34.640 --> 00:12:36.400
Um. that was such a long day.

184
00:12:54.320 --> 00:12:56.480
As we are getting closer to the island.

185
00:12:56.560 --> 00:12:58.640
I see that we're getting too close.

186
00:12:58.720 --> 00:13:02.560
so I mention this to the head waiter
who's standing next to me.

187
00:13:02.640 --> 00:13:05.200
I said. "I think
we're getting a little too close."

188
00:13:07.360 --> 00:13:10.360
Suddenly.
the shore became clearly visible.

189
00:13:12.680 --> 00:13:14.360
On this particular night.

190
00:13:14.440 --> 00:13:17.320
with my friends.
we had the half-hour break.

191
00:13:17.840 --> 00:13:21.760
I was dating one of the barmen from Peru.

192
00:13:21.840 --> 00:13:25.720
who was working in the Londra Bar
at the back of Deck 5.

193
00:13:25.800 --> 00:13:27.840
at the back of the ship.
and I wanted to see him.

194
00:13:27.920 --> 00:13:29.640
so I said to everybody else.

195
00:13:29.720 --> 00:13:33.280
I was like. "Do you wanna go get
a cappuccino in the Londra Bar?"

196
00:13:33.360 --> 00:13:36.080
And so everyone was like.
"Oh yeah. let's go do that."

197
00:13:52.200 --> 00:13:56.440
As the ship got closer to the island.

198
00:13:57.200 --> 00:14:01.600
what surprised me quite a bit
was that the ship never slowed down.

199
00:14:04.960 --> 00:14:07.280
In that moment. I started to panic.

200
00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:26.440
The head waiter tells me. "No. look."

201
00:14:26.520 --> 00:14:29.200
"The captain knows very well
what he is doing."

202
00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:31.320
And then he didn't finish the sentence.

203
00:14:46.240 --> 00:14:51.000
I heard and felt a sound and a vibration.

204
00:14:51.080 --> 00:14:55.480
For me. the room starting to slowly shift
just was incredibly unnerving.

205
00:14:57.440 --> 00:15:01.960
You know. my body tensed up.
and I knew something was terribly wrong.

206
00:15:02.560 --> 00:15:05.040
We heard a loud screeching sound.

207
00:15:06.280 --> 00:15:11.320
And then the noise changes
from a screech to a scraping noise.

208
00:15:12.680 --> 00:15:14.680
and that's a terrifying noise to hear.

209
00:15:19.960 --> 00:15:22.640
Can you imagine
a thousand plates breaking in one time?

210
00:15:23.240 --> 00:15:27.040
I was so scared
because the sound was really high.

211
00:15:30.520 --> 00:15:35.280
And all this boiling water
from the braiser starts falling down.

212
00:15:37.680 --> 00:15:40.280
I was one of 180 chefs.

213
00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:42.360
No one knows what's happening.

214
00:15:42.440 --> 00:15:45.760
I thought it's rough sea.
and it's gonna be all right.

215
00:15:45.840 --> 00:15:47.680
And after a few seconds…

216
00:15:48.720 --> 00:15:51.400
no. it's something not right.

217
00:16:12.320 --> 00:16:14.040
I turned and saw

218
00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:18.040
that the ship had crashed into the rocks
on the left side.

219
00:16:19.120 --> 00:16:24.000
You could literally see
the water entering the ship's hull.

220
00:16:35.440 --> 00:16:39.720
We were all shocked and unable to move.

221
00:16:41.840 --> 00:16:43.440
Calm down.

222
00:16:43.520 --> 00:16:45.840
-It's better if you sit down.
-Sit down?

223
00:16:45.920 --> 00:16:47.200
-Sit down?
-Yes.

224
00:16:50.880 --> 00:16:53.160
Everyone was freaking out.

225
00:16:53.880 --> 00:16:57.480
And I was looking at my mum
that was right in front of me.

226
00:16:57.560 --> 00:17:02.280
She looked at me and said. "It's okay."

227
00:17:02.360 --> 00:17:03.560
"Everything okay."

228
00:17:05.319 --> 00:17:07.359
She was trying to do everything

229
00:17:07.440 --> 00:17:11.240
to make me feel like
nothing bad was happening.

230
00:17:11.319 --> 00:17:14.000
but I knew it was.

231
00:17:18.560 --> 00:17:22.160
We're just standing there.
looking at what to do next.

232
00:17:23.599 --> 00:17:27.480
I quickly stopped having any emotion.

233
00:17:27.560 --> 00:17:30.080
and I looked at Nicholas. and he said.

234
00:17:30.840 --> 00:17:34.240
"We need to get out of here.
and we need to get out of here now."

235
00:17:36.360 --> 00:17:39.080
He said. "Did you hear that?
Did you feel that?"

236
00:17:39.600 --> 00:17:40.880
I definitely felt panic.

237
00:17:41.920 --> 00:17:45.800
and so my body sort of goes
into this crisis-response mode.

238
00:17:46.920 --> 00:17:49.720
You know. I've been accused of being
an unemotional person.

239
00:17:50.280 --> 00:17:53.000
but at that moment.
it was just pure survival

240
00:17:53.080 --> 00:17:55.720
and just trying to lead my family out
of this thing.

241
00:17:57.960 --> 00:18:00.000
I yelled to Meghan.
I said. "Grab the baby."

242
00:18:00.080 --> 00:18:01.280
Like. "We've gotta go."

243
00:18:03.600 --> 00:18:05.680
Seeing him react the way that he did.

244
00:18:05.760 --> 00:18:08.080
I immediately felt dread.

245
00:18:08.160 --> 00:18:12.120
I grabbed Lila out of the crib
in the middle of a deep sleep.

246
00:18:12.200 --> 00:18:15.040
At that point.
I had not grabbed the pacifier.

247
00:18:15.120 --> 00:18:17.880
She was crying immediately.

248
00:18:19.440 --> 00:18:22.120
I threw on jeans. but that was it.

249
00:18:22.200 --> 00:18:25.920
I didn't have a shirt on.
Meghan had Lila in her arms.

250
00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.360
And we ran out the door.

251
00:18:31.680 --> 00:18:34.320
As soon as the impact occurred.

252
00:18:34.400 --> 00:18:37.720
my first thought is to go and see
what happened down there.

253
00:18:37.800 --> 00:18:40.080
And near the machine room.

254
00:18:40.160 --> 00:18:43.560
the chief engineer comes out.
all alarmed and scared.

255
00:18:43.640 --> 00:18:47.360
He tells me it's a disaster downstairs.
water entering at full force.

256
00:18:47.960 --> 00:18:49.480
I felt helpless.

257
00:19:46.840 --> 00:19:49.560
We burst out the door into the hallway.

258
00:19:49.640 --> 00:19:52.760
I was thinking the ship was just gonna be
slowly tipping over.

259
00:19:52.840 --> 00:19:56.440
and in my head. It was just a race
to get to the lifeboat deck.

260
00:19:57.600 --> 00:20:02.000
And so we started just racing
up the stairs as fast as we could.

261
00:20:02.080 --> 00:20:04.240
Meghan and the baby behind me.

262
00:20:08.480 --> 00:20:11.640
The adrenaline starts rushing.
Panic was hitting.

263
00:20:12.960 --> 00:20:15.520
Lila's been crying the whole time.

264
00:20:16.040 --> 00:20:17.920
We were taking stairs two by two.

265
00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:20.280
and I was holding the baby.
trying to keep up.

266
00:20:20.840 --> 00:20:22.160
I was struggling.

267
00:20:22.240 --> 00:20:24.200
I felt physically sick.

268
00:20:25.440 --> 00:20:27.520
I said. "I think I'm gonna throw up."

269
00:20:28.040 --> 00:20:30.000
John said.
"Just throw up and keep running."

270
00:20:30.080 --> 00:20:31.480
"Just don't stop. Just keep going."

271
00:20:37.240 --> 00:20:40.720
We got to the fourth level deck
where the lifeboats are.

272
00:20:40.800 --> 00:20:43.680
And there was a couple
that passed out life vests to everybody.

273
00:20:44.280 --> 00:20:46.840
At this point. it was only a few people.

274
00:20:46.920 --> 00:20:49.560
and there was this ice of anxiety
that you have

275
00:20:49.640 --> 00:20:51.560
with no one giving you information.

276
00:20:52.080 --> 00:20:55.360
No one was instructing us what to do.

277
00:20:57.400 --> 00:20:59.760
And right then. the lights went out.

278
00:21:07.800 --> 00:21:09.320
It was just pitch black.

279
00:21:12.160 --> 00:21:14.960
Suddenly I'm being separated
from Meghan and Lila.

280
00:21:18.480 --> 00:21:20.800
I don't know
if it was three stairs or 13 stairs.

281
00:21:20.880 --> 00:21:22.520
but they were not next to me.

282
00:21:23.880 --> 00:21:25.080
I was scared.

283
00:21:25.160 --> 00:21:27.120
and I remember yelling for him.

284
00:21:27.200 --> 00:21:28.560
"John! John!"

285
00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:34.200
Yelling. following each other's voices.

286
00:21:35.720 --> 00:21:37.480
It felt like an eternity.

287
00:21:40.920 --> 00:21:42.880
When we did reconnect. I remember saying.

288
00:21:42.960 --> 00:21:46.600
"Just grab my waistline on my jeans
and don't let go."

289
00:21:47.360 --> 00:21:51.480
I had Lila in my arms
and just continued up two steps at a time.

290
00:21:55.920 --> 00:21:58.880
The chief engineer
came to the bridge with me.

291
00:21:58.960 --> 00:22:01.800
Together with Captain Schettino.
they open the ship plans

292
00:22:01.880 --> 00:22:07.360
and try to understand the damage
the ship has really suffered.

293
00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:21.880
On the bridge.
the sound of the impact was hardly felt.

294
00:22:23.200 --> 00:22:27.160
while the people who were
in the restaurant in the back area.

295
00:22:27.240 --> 00:22:32.640
they felt the full force of the impact.

296
00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:05.040
<i>Your attention. please.</i>

297
00:23:05.120 --> 00:23:06.800
<i>I speak on behalf of the captain.</i>

298
00:23:06.880 --> 00:23:10.240
<i>We're currently in a blackout</i>
<i>as we're experiencing electrical failure.</i>

299
00:23:10.320 --> 00:23:12.400
<i>At this point.</i>
<i>the situation is under control.</i>

300
00:23:12.480 --> 00:23:15.160
<i>and our technicians</i>
<i>are working to solve the situation.</i>

301
00:23:15.240 --> 00:23:18.640
<i>We'll give you further information</i>
<i>as it becomes available.</i>

302
00:23:19.800 --> 00:23:25.120
They continued to say things like.
"Don't worry. everything is fine."

303
00:23:25.200 --> 00:23:27.400
-"Go back to your room."
-"Go back to your room."

304
00:23:28.200 --> 00:23:31.240
<i>We have made</i>
<i>an announcement on behalf of the captain.</i>

305
00:23:31.320 --> 00:23:34.440
<i>We kindly ask you</i>
<i>to go back to your cabin.</i>

306
00:23:34.960 --> 00:23:38.520
I kept thinkin'.
"I'm not gonna go back to my room."

307
00:23:38.600 --> 00:23:41.600
-No way.
-There's no way.

308
00:23:41.680 --> 00:23:44.920
I don't even know if I could find the room
at that point. to be honest.

309
00:23:45.600 --> 00:23:47.560

310
00:23:47.640 --> 00:23:51.120
I see that the passengers are very scared.

311
00:23:51.200 --> 00:23:53.880
and they are asking me what has happened.

312
00:23:54.640 --> 00:23:58.080
And. not to go against
what the captain has said.

313
00:23:58.160 --> 00:24:03.080
I couldn't give them a different version
as I would only do more damage.

314
00:24:03.760 --> 00:24:06.120
The inability to act. This is the problem.

315
00:24:13.720 --> 00:24:16.240
We don't know what's happening.

316
00:24:17.480 --> 00:24:20.640
Every announcement we heard. we believe.

317
00:24:21.320 --> 00:24:23.960
We heard. okay. there is a minor fault.

318
00:24:24.480 --> 00:24:28.200
The captain. whatever he said.
that's the final word.

319
00:24:29.400 --> 00:24:34.160
And I heard the chef saying.
"Oh. nobody… Don't move. Don't move."

320
00:24:34.240 --> 00:24:38.920
"Just stay there where you are
and be ready for the dinner service."

321
00:24:44.760 --> 00:24:48.480
It felt like it was a long time
before the lights came back on.

322
00:24:49.080 --> 00:24:51.400
We're still running up the stairs.

323
00:24:52.280 --> 00:24:56.680
And then finally we entered out
into the deck where the lifeboats were.

324
00:25:02.120 --> 00:25:04.800
Hundreds and hundreds of people
shoulder to shoulder.

325
00:25:05.320 --> 00:25:07.880
You're hit with a wall of panic.

326
00:25:09.600 --> 00:25:13.520
People yelling. arguing. trying to decide
what to do. what's going on.

327
00:25:15.520 --> 00:25:17.120
Every crew member saying.

328
00:25:17.200 --> 00:25:20.400
"There's been an electrical failure
or issue. We're not evacuating."

329
00:25:22.120 --> 00:25:25.000
Lila is in my arms. still crying.

330
00:25:26.520 --> 00:25:28.040
I was a new mother.

331
00:25:28.120 --> 00:25:31.160
and so the loss of control of

332
00:25:31.880 --> 00:25:34.360
not having a way to help her…

333
00:25:35.320 --> 00:25:39.800
My primary focus was
on the nurturing and comfort of my child.

334
00:25:42.480 --> 00:25:46.000
It was very hard
hearing and seeing Meghan struggle.

335
00:25:50.120 --> 00:25:54.360
And at that point.
I remember looking John in the eye

336
00:25:54.880 --> 00:25:57.400
and saying. "I want to get off the ship."

337
00:26:04.320 --> 00:26:09.200
In this endless
period of general confusion.

338
00:26:09.280 --> 00:26:14.560
the captain was often on the phone
with the company crisis coordinator.

339
00:26:30.280 --> 00:26:32.920
They didn't tell the truth
because. in my opinion.

340
00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:38.600
the captain was fully panicking.

341
00:26:38.680 --> 00:26:42.720
He couldn't understand what had happened.

342
00:26:55.680 --> 00:26:57.320
In the restaurant.

343
00:26:57.400 --> 00:27:03.480
we looked at the crew
for some direction on what to do.

344
00:27:03.560 --> 00:27:06.600
but they seemed in panic.

345
00:27:13.800 --> 00:27:17.640
Then finally. the waiters told us
to reach the pool deck.

346
00:27:18.160 --> 00:27:21.720
Everybody was scrambling

347
00:27:21.800 --> 00:27:24.480
because everyone was panicking.

348
00:27:27.120 --> 00:27:29.920
Exit the other side. please.
Exit the other side.

349
00:27:34.040 --> 00:27:37.880
There was a lot
of broken dishes and glasses on the floor.

350
00:27:37.960 --> 00:27:40.800
and we were dressed up for the dinner.

351
00:27:40.880 --> 00:27:43.240
so we wore high heels.

352
00:27:44.760 --> 00:27:48.000
But finally. we reached the pool deck.

353
00:27:48.760 --> 00:27:52.000
and I remember. I looked out the windows.

354
00:27:52.520 --> 00:27:54.280
I saw Giglio Island.

355
00:27:55.280 --> 00:27:57.640
Look. there's the coast.
There's no problem.

356
00:27:57.720 --> 00:28:01.560
Look. Alice. look at the land.
We have arrived!

357
00:28:02.640 --> 00:28:05.240
We could see the lights.

358
00:28:05.320 --> 00:28:08.240
We could see the… you know. the port.

359
00:28:09.320 --> 00:28:15.080
So I say. "Oh. Oh. okay.
we are just… next to the land.

360
00:28:15.160 --> 00:28:18.040
so it's okay. It's gonna be fine."

361
00:28:19.480 --> 00:28:21.480
Many people relaxed.

362
00:28:22.120 --> 00:28:24.120
and that's where the problem is.

363
00:28:24.200 --> 00:28:26.560
We lowered our defenses.

364
00:28:48.400 --> 00:28:51.920
There were three chefs.
They were stuck in the elevator.

365
00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:56.440
They were shouting
and knocking the elevator door.

366
00:28:59.440 --> 00:29:00.880
Four people went there.

367
00:29:01.680 --> 00:29:05.400
And we forced the door to open.
and we took them out.

368
00:29:11.440 --> 00:29:14.960
At the back of Deck 5.
the ship was listing more and more.

369
00:29:17.040 --> 00:29:20.120
I remember thinking to myself.
"I can't stay here."

370
00:29:20.200 --> 00:29:22.360
"I need to get off the ship."

371
00:29:25.800 --> 00:29:29.760
And as I'm walking along the corridor.
I see my superior.

372
00:29:30.280 --> 00:29:32.680
She sees me.
and she says. "Where are you going?"

373
00:29:32.760 --> 00:29:34.720
And I say.
"I'm going to my muster station."

374
00:29:34.800 --> 00:29:36.040
She said. "No. you're not."

375
00:29:36.120 --> 00:29:40.320
"You're gonna go back into the lounge.
and you're going to entertain passengers."

376
00:29:40.400 --> 00:29:44.080
And I couldn't believe what I was hearing.

377
00:29:44.160 --> 00:29:46.080
and I said. "I quit."

378
00:29:47.200 --> 00:29:49.080
I went straight to my muster station.

379
00:29:49.160 --> 00:29:52.040
I didn't wait for any code. any signal.

380
00:29:52.120 --> 00:29:53.400
any mayday. nothing.

381
00:29:56.800 --> 00:29:59.080
I'm on Deck 4.
I'm at the front of the ship.

382
00:29:59.160 --> 00:30:00.400
We. the crew.

383
00:30:00.480 --> 00:30:03.360
we're in a completely segregated.
different area.

384
00:30:06.960 --> 00:30:09.760
My superior officer was supposed to come.

385
00:30:09.840 --> 00:30:11.600
but when he arrived.

386
00:30:12.920 --> 00:30:14.280
it was like seeing a ghost.

387
00:30:14.360 --> 00:30:17.840
He was completely white. Completely white.

388
00:30:17.920 --> 00:30:21.360
There was nothing behind his eyes.
I felt like I was seeing a zombie.

389
00:30:21.440 --> 00:30:23.320
He had his… his engineer suit on.

390
00:30:23.400 --> 00:30:26.360
which is kind of like a onesie
or a Babygro.

391
00:30:26.440 --> 00:30:30.640
It's like an all-in-one.
and it was completely drenched in water.

392
00:30:30.720 --> 00:30:34.360
And when he came.
he wasn't able to communicate.

393
00:30:34.880 --> 00:30:38.880
It was at that point that I was like.
"Okay. we've got no leadership."

394
00:30:38.960 --> 00:30:40.440
"It's falling to me."

395
00:30:46.880 --> 00:30:50.920
I am on the bridge.
and I say to the officers.

396
00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:53.800
"Look. the ship
is already tilting 20 degrees."

397
00:30:54.320 --> 00:30:58.960
So a light should've gone off
in their head. since it is their job.

398
00:30:59.040 --> 00:31:01.520
and they should know
that the more the ship tilts.

399
00:31:01.600 --> 00:31:04.440
the more stability is lost.

400
00:31:08.520 --> 00:31:10.360
The level of the water

401
00:31:10.440 --> 00:31:12.720
was now getting closer and closer

402
00:31:12.800 --> 00:31:14.440
to where we were at.

403
00:31:14.520 --> 00:31:18.120
What seemed to be
so far from the lifeboats

404
00:31:18.200 --> 00:31:21.440
is now creeping closer and closer
to where we were.

405
00:31:21.520 --> 00:31:27.480
and I was kinda getting
more panicked and scared.

406
00:31:27.560 --> 00:31:30.880
and I started to film
everything that I could.

407
00:31:33.120 --> 00:31:34.760
People having to grab the side

408
00:31:34.840 --> 00:31:39.000
in order to stay from sliding
to the side of the boat.

409
00:31:40.600 --> 00:31:43.440
No one's telling us what to do.

410
00:31:43.520 --> 00:31:45.480
and then Nicholas said…

411
00:31:45.560 --> 00:31:48.280
"This boat's going down.
We need to get off."

412
00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:51.760
Wait. wait. Her husband. her husband.

413
00:31:51.840 --> 00:31:54.360
So we opened up the lifeboat.
and when we got in there.

414
00:31:54.440 --> 00:31:56.560
we started looking
at. like. you know. the pulley system

415
00:31:56.640 --> 00:31:57.800
and then also the motors.

416
00:31:57.880 --> 00:31:59.520
I'm getting pushed!

417
00:31:59.600 --> 00:32:00.800
I'm…

418
00:32:00.880 --> 00:32:04.200
We actually now start to see
what looks like a chef.

419
00:32:04.280 --> 00:32:06.920
and he's got a life vest on.

420
00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:08.960
He comes and tells us.

421
00:32:09.040 --> 00:32:11.000
"You are not supposed to touch
all of this."

422
00:32:11.080 --> 00:32:12.680
He closes the gate.

423
00:32:14.280 --> 00:32:18.000
-Hey. hey. hey. one by one.
-What do you wanna say?

424
00:32:18.080 --> 00:32:20.400
I'm getting a bit louder.
"This doesn't make sense."

425
00:32:20.480 --> 00:32:22.240
"We need to get off this boat."

426
00:32:22.320 --> 00:32:25.360
And we're kinda starting to freak out.

427
00:32:26.080 --> 00:32:28.080
It was very evident

428
00:32:28.160 --> 00:32:31.360
that it wasn't only a blackout.

429
00:32:31.440 --> 00:32:33.880
that the passengers stopped believing this

430
00:32:34.440 --> 00:32:38.240
and started calling the police.

431
00:33:48.680 --> 00:33:50.800
They were saying
there had been a blackout.

432
00:33:50.880 --> 00:33:53.280
but they weren't telling them
the reality of the situation.

433
00:33:53.800 --> 00:33:57.600
The captain probably wanted
to exonerate himself

434
00:33:57.680 --> 00:33:59.600
from what was happening.

435
00:34:00.200 --> 00:34:03.000
Which is very wrong. in my opinion.

436
00:34:06.840 --> 00:34:10.679
Some chef comes up and says.

437
00:34:10.760 --> 00:34:13.239
"You know what?
Something big has happened.

438
00:34:13.320 --> 00:34:17.159
and Deck C is leaking."

439
00:34:18.080 --> 00:34:21.400
When he said Deck C is leaking.
I forgot everything.

440
00:34:21.480 --> 00:34:23.440
I run to the downstairs.

441
00:34:23.960 --> 00:34:25.760
because whenever I get paid.

442
00:34:25.840 --> 00:34:29.480
I used to keep my money under the bed.

443
00:34:30.480 --> 00:34:32.560
I was in a lot of debt.

444
00:34:33.080 --> 00:34:35.480
I had put my family in trouble.

445
00:34:36.320 --> 00:34:42.320
I was keep thinking every day I will
get enough money to pay all my debt.

446
00:34:44.360 --> 00:34:47.639
All my hard work. everything that I save.

447
00:34:48.159 --> 00:34:49.760
under my bed.

448
00:34:51.360 --> 00:34:53.880
So I have to get my money.

449
00:34:53.960 --> 00:34:58.000
which I have in my cabin in Deck B.

450
00:35:01.080 --> 00:35:05.200
I see chief security guard standing there.

451
00:35:06.120 --> 00:35:08.440
and he was stopping me. saying.

452
00:35:08.520 --> 00:35:11.640
"You're not… you're not allowed
to go in Deck B."

453
00:35:11.720 --> 00:35:15.400
He said. "No one is allowed in this area."

454
00:35:15.480 --> 00:35:19.320
I said. "But I have
very important things to take."

455
00:35:19.400 --> 00:35:22.240
He said.
"Nothing important than your life."

456
00:35:23.600 --> 00:35:25.200
He was right.

457
00:35:25.720 --> 00:35:28.600
I have to get to my lifeboat.

458
00:36:13.560 --> 00:36:16.000
On the bridge. there is a lot of chaos.

459
00:36:16.080 --> 00:36:21.720
The other officers are speechless.
They don't know what to do.

460
00:36:21.800 --> 00:36:26.080
And at this point. they hit
the general emergency button.

461
00:36:26.600 --> 00:36:28.480
and the blasts are triggered.

462
00:36:31.680 --> 00:36:36.000
Suddenly. we heard the first siren blast.

463
00:36:37.200 --> 00:36:40.960
At that moment. everybody went quiet.

464
00:36:43.040 --> 00:36:46.640
We heard one horn and then a second horn.

465
00:36:46.720 --> 00:36:48.440
And about this time. I think.

466
00:36:48.520 --> 00:36:51.640
"No shit." you know? That this is
what we've been waiting on all night.

467
00:36:53.160 --> 00:36:56.960
This was probably
one of the ugliest points of the evening

468
00:36:57.040 --> 00:37:01.080
because it was just hundreds of people
fighting to push through each other

469
00:37:01.160 --> 00:37:03.800
and push over each other
to get to these life rafts.

470
00:37:04.520 --> 00:37:05.560
Hey. hey!

471
00:37:05.640 --> 00:37:09.160
I was being shoved around
by people my father's age.

472
00:37:11.800 --> 00:37:14.520
<i>Ladies and gentlemen.</i>
<i>your attention. please.</i>

473
00:37:14.600 --> 00:37:18.560
<i>Please remain calm</i>
<i>and go to your muster station on Deck 4</i>

474
00:37:18.640 --> 00:37:22.440
Military mentality prevails on the ship.

475
00:37:22.520 --> 00:37:26.120
Hierarchy is important.
Each person has a role.

476
00:37:27.040 --> 00:37:31.720
Why did it take them 45 minutes
to call a general emergency?

477
00:37:32.480 --> 00:37:36.200
I think the captain wanted to see
how the situation evolved.

478
00:37:36.800 --> 00:37:41.200
In my opinion. it should have been sounded
no later than five minutes after impact.

479
00:37:42.920 --> 00:37:45.000
I went down to Deck 4

480
00:37:45.080 --> 00:37:47.760
to try to save as many people as possible

481
00:37:47.840 --> 00:37:50.320
and lead the rescue operations.

482
00:37:53.280 --> 00:37:54.920
The ship was tilted.

483
00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:58.680
and my mother began to struggle
with her heels.

484
00:37:59.920 --> 00:38:03.120
She held my hand really tight

485
00:38:03.200 --> 00:38:05.920
and said. "Don't let me go."

486
00:38:15.800 --> 00:38:17.480
At this moment.

487
00:38:18.160 --> 00:38:20.360
we. without saying a word.

488
00:38:20.440 --> 00:38:22.960
looked at each other
and knew what we had to do.

489
00:38:24.440 --> 00:38:26.560
One by one. one by one.

490
00:38:27.080 --> 00:38:30.120
Get the kids. go. go. You. you. you. you.

491
00:38:30.200 --> 00:38:32.480
And we start
getting people into the lifeboat.

492
00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:35.800
You never know
what kind of person you are.

493
00:38:35.880 --> 00:38:38.120
like. flight or fight.

494
00:38:38.200 --> 00:38:41.040
You never know
if you're gonna be that person

495
00:38:41.120 --> 00:38:43.400
that's just gonna stand there still

496
00:38:43.480 --> 00:38:45.240
or go into action.

497
00:38:45.320 --> 00:38:47.600
You go. you go.

498
00:39:02.760 --> 00:39:04.440
Bring the children here.

499
00:39:04.960 --> 00:39:06.760
Bring the children here.

500
00:39:08.040 --> 00:39:10.320
The lifeboats can only hold 150 people.

501
00:39:10.400 --> 00:39:13.400
so you have to make sure
there's only 150 people.

502
00:39:13.480 --> 00:39:16.000
Stop. We're going to capsize.

503
00:39:16.080 --> 00:39:17.960
We're going to capsize. Stop!

504
00:39:19.760 --> 00:39:21.080
Stop!

505
00:39:22.400 --> 00:39:23.520
Stop!

506
00:39:30.440 --> 00:39:31.720
No. no. no!

507
00:39:32.240 --> 00:39:34.280
We've got quite a few people on the boat.

508
00:39:34.360 --> 00:39:36.040
close to the 150-people maximum.

509
00:39:37.520 --> 00:39:42.280
People are offering money
to get on a boat. It was very sad.

510
00:39:43.800 --> 00:39:45.840
One of 'em was. like.
a little bit more elderly.

511
00:39:45.920 --> 00:39:47.560
and I was just like. "Oh man."

512
00:39:49.680 --> 00:39:51.800
-What is your name?
-Nicholas Taliaferro.

513
00:39:51.880 --> 00:39:54.520
-From where? Nicholas?
-San Diego. California.

514
00:39:54.600 --> 00:39:55.800
It's very helpful.

515
00:39:55.880 --> 00:39:58.560
I was sitting waiting in the lifeboat.

516
00:39:59.640 --> 00:40:06.320
There's a point that people wanted to say
their names on the camera.

517
00:40:06.840 --> 00:40:10.160
We're Steve and Kathy.
from Port Huron. Michigan.

518
00:40:11.680 --> 00:40:13.400
We're Marie and Melissa.

519
00:40:13.480 --> 00:40:18.120
-We're gonna stay together.
-Yes. we're gonna stay together.

520
00:40:19.520 --> 00:40:21.800
It's so eerie

521
00:40:21.880 --> 00:40:24.680
because they thought they were gonna die.

522
00:40:30.480 --> 00:40:32.400
We were on the high side of the ship.

523
00:40:32.480 --> 00:40:34.320
There's just dozens and dozens of people

524
00:40:34.400 --> 00:40:38.400
piling into what essentially is.
like. a metal canister.

525
00:40:38.480 --> 00:40:41.880
Then we eventually had
our turn to get into the lifeboat.

526
00:40:41.960 --> 00:40:45.080
"Let's get this life raft
actually down into the water."

527
00:40:45.160 --> 00:40:48.080
Everybody. once they were on.
was just dying to hear that order.

528
00:40:49.280 --> 00:40:51.200
Think we might be ready to go.

529
00:40:51.280 --> 00:40:53.920
I looked at the people in the lifeboats.

530
00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:56.240
and they were scared.

531
00:40:56.760 --> 00:41:01.680
They were waiting for the signal
of abandon ship.

532
00:41:03.960 --> 00:41:07.320
<i>Yes. but why are they</i>
<i>not sending the lifeboats down?</i>

533
00:41:12.320 --> 00:41:15.640
We were expecting this signal.
to abandon ship.

534
00:41:16.560 --> 00:41:19.920
But it was slow to arrive.
and it was not clear why.

535
00:41:20.760 --> 00:41:24.480
And I noticed
everybody was wearing a life jacket.

536
00:41:24.560 --> 00:41:26.520
but we didn't find one.

537
00:41:27.400 --> 00:41:31.120
And I remember Luisa looked at my mother.

538
00:41:31.640 --> 00:41:33.640
and she said. "I can't swim."

539
00:41:33.720 --> 00:41:35.800
She was pretty scared.

540
00:41:36.840 --> 00:41:41.680
My mother said.
"I need to go to the cabin."

541
00:41:41.760 --> 00:41:44.280
"I need to get Luisa's life jacket.

542
00:41:44.360 --> 00:41:49.160
and also I will change my shoes
because I can't walk anymore."

543
00:41:49.240 --> 00:41:51.360
And I say. "No!"

544
00:41:51.440 --> 00:41:54.560
"This is the worst idea ever."

545
00:41:54.640 --> 00:41:58.840
"There's no way
I'm going back to our cabin."

546
00:41:58.920 --> 00:42:00.240
"It's two deck below."

547
00:42:00.760 --> 00:42:04.000
And she said. "We are going."

548
00:42:04.080 --> 00:42:06.600
"If you don't want to come with us.

549
00:42:07.200 --> 00:42:10.280
you can just wait here with Andrea."

550
00:42:30.680 --> 00:42:32.480

551
00:42:32.560 --> 00:42:35.280
Yes. they're coming down.
I see them. I see them.

552
00:42:58.360 --> 00:43:01.080
As soon as I entered the lifeboat.

553
00:43:01.160 --> 00:43:02.920
I called my mother.

554
00:43:03.840 --> 00:43:05.840
and I said. "Where are you?"

555
00:43:08.920 --> 00:43:13.560
She told me
she was about to get onto a lifeboat too.

556
00:43:14.640 --> 00:43:17.200
We are going down. We are going down.

557
00:43:19.200 --> 00:43:23.600
Just because we were on the lifeboat
didn't make us feel any better.

558
00:43:23.680 --> 00:43:25.680
Hands in. hands in.

559
00:43:26.640 --> 00:43:31.280
When it went
to slowly go down to the waterline.

560
00:43:31.360 --> 00:43:35.640
we started holding hands
and say "Our Father."

561
00:43:36.240 --> 00:43:41.720
And we said it repeatedly and repeatedly
and over and over and over again.

562
00:43:42.560 --> 00:43:45.280
"We are gonna do this together."

563
00:43:50.200 --> 00:43:53.680
We could see what would've been our room.

564
00:43:53.760 --> 00:43:57.600
which was above where the lifeboats were.

565
00:43:57.680 --> 00:44:02.400
was… was right at water level
at this point.

566
00:44:03.960 --> 00:44:06.280
Oh. look at that list. Holy shit!

567
00:44:07.840 --> 00:44:10.840
Oh my God. the boat is sinking.

568
00:44:11.680 --> 00:44:14.160
Sh! We don't wanna be
yelling it out loud. guys.

569
00:44:14.240 --> 00:44:16.840
That would scare the shit outta me
if I was up there.

570
00:44:17.360 --> 00:44:18.800
Glad to be outta there.

571
00:44:19.840 --> 00:44:24.880
I saw the crew member getting
the go-ahead to deploy the lifeboat.

572
00:44:24.960 --> 00:44:28.040
and I remember thinking. "Thank God."

573
00:44:28.120 --> 00:44:31.960
We finally had gotten this close
to getting off the boat.

574
00:44:32.840 --> 00:44:35.040
We were on a high side at this point.

575
00:44:35.560 --> 00:44:37.240
I was holding Lila.

576
00:44:37.320 --> 00:44:39.880
and then. within seconds.

577
00:44:40.400 --> 00:44:43.280
I had the feeling
of. like. a rollercoaster ride

578
00:44:43.360 --> 00:44:44.680
where your stomach drops.

579
00:44:53.760 --> 00:44:56.440
It was a big drop.
a big bang. and then a tumble.

580
00:44:56.520 --> 00:45:00.160
God. now I am scared!

581
00:45:01.920 --> 00:45:05.600
The lifeboat tipped. and it
basically flung 80 people in that boat.

582
00:45:07.960 --> 00:45:10.440
Piles of people
just slamming against one another.

583
00:45:10.520 --> 00:45:15.240
You're just a mangling of bodies
and people screaming and crying.

584
00:45:17.880 --> 00:45:19.600
With the ship at an angle.

585
00:45:19.680 --> 00:45:22.640
they basically deployed the lifeboat
right into the side of the cruise ship.

586
00:45:29.520 --> 00:45:33.320
We were on what was now
the high side of the lifeboat

587
00:45:33.840 --> 00:45:37.240
and basically holding ourselves up
with our feet.

588
00:45:37.760 --> 00:45:40.200
I was bleeding.
You know. our feet were bleeding.

589
00:45:41.720 --> 00:45:44.520
Lila's crying is just shattering Meghan.

590
00:45:45.040 --> 00:45:47.680
I remember crying out to John.

591
00:45:48.200 --> 00:45:50.560
you know. "John.
I'm not gonna be able to hold Lila."

592
00:45:51.560 --> 00:45:53.760
And I handed Lila to you.

593
00:45:54.480 --> 00:45:56.720
It was an extremely precarious situation.

594
00:45:58.320 --> 00:46:00.720
I don't know
whether the thing was gonna drop

595
00:46:01.520 --> 00:46:03.680
because we were high off of the waterline.

596
00:46:04.520 --> 00:46:08.160
Below us on the lifeboat. there were
clearly people that needed help.

597
00:46:08.680 --> 00:46:10.680
but I…

598
00:46:10.760 --> 00:46:14.080
My entire focus was on saving my family.

599
00:46:15.920 --> 00:46:18.680
We really didn't know
how we could get outta this thing.

600
00:46:21.600 --> 00:46:24.880
At that point. I heard myself say.

601
00:46:24.960 --> 00:46:26.160
"Are we gonna die?"

602
00:46:50.440 --> 00:46:52.760

603
00:46:52.840 --> 00:46:55.640
The captain found it difficult
to give this order

604
00:46:55.720 --> 00:47:01.440
because when the captain says
abandon ship. the ship is lost.

605
00:47:05.600 --> 00:47:08.400
People are leaving the ship. but for me.

606
00:47:08.480 --> 00:47:11.840
it was real bad situation.
I was still in the ship.

607
00:47:11.920 --> 00:47:14.480
I was really scared
because I don't know swimming.

608
00:47:16.040 --> 00:47:18.200
In order to join in the cruise line.

609
00:47:18.280 --> 00:47:21.920
you have to be trained by swimming.

610
00:47:22.800 --> 00:47:25.440
But my institute.
they put me in a life jacket.

611
00:47:25.520 --> 00:47:27.560
and they just pushed me
in the swimming pool.

612
00:47:27.640 --> 00:47:32.040
And I was floating. and the next minute.
they took me out from the pool.

613
00:47:32.120 --> 00:47:34.520
and they said.
"Yeah. your training is done."

614
00:47:35.160 --> 00:47:37.000
So I don't know what to do.

615
00:47:37.080 --> 00:47:39.520
The ship was falling. like. really fast.

616
00:47:40.040 --> 00:47:41.280
"I'm… I'm going to die."

617
00:47:44.120 --> 00:47:46.440
And then one of my colleagues saw me

618
00:47:46.520 --> 00:47:48.840
with my wet eyes.
and he said. "Come with me."

619
00:47:50.120 --> 00:47:52.440
The water had reached Deck 3.

620
00:47:52.520 --> 00:47:56.240
and he guided me to Deck 4
on the other side.

621
00:47:58.040 --> 00:48:01.760
I reach other side. and I get in the boat.

622
00:48:06.080 --> 00:48:10.160
When I left.
I can see a lot of people still inside.

623
00:48:10.240 --> 00:48:13.240
They were struggling to… to be rescued.

624
00:48:14.800 --> 00:48:17.240
I didn't believe it's happening.

625
00:48:17.880 --> 00:48:21.040
I was still thinking it must be a dream.

626
00:48:22.320 --> 00:48:24.240
And one of my friends was working with me.

627
00:48:24.320 --> 00:48:27.440
and he just told me and said.
"Hey. you see?"

628
00:48:29.040 --> 00:48:31.400
"Captain is sitting in the lifeboat."

629
00:48:32.680 --> 00:48:34.040
And that was surprising me.

630
00:48:34.120 --> 00:48:37.560
Why captain need to get out before me?

631
00:48:42.120 --> 00:48:43.800
It's tilting.

632
00:48:43.880 --> 00:48:46.360

633
00:48:46.440 --> 00:48:48.920
Look at that!

634
00:48:49.680 --> 00:48:51.600
As the ship was sinking.

635
00:48:51.680 --> 00:48:54.640
we kept tilting and tilting and tilting.
We couldn't stand up.

636
00:48:54.720 --> 00:48:58.520
so we rearranged ourselves
onto the side of the ship.

637
00:48:59.400 --> 00:49:03.760
What we were also seeing
on this high part of the ship.

638
00:49:04.280 --> 00:49:07.520
there was a lifeboat
that was trying to deploy and go down.

639
00:49:07.600 --> 00:49:09.640
and. because of the angle of the ship.

640
00:49:09.720 --> 00:49:11.600
the lifeboat was rolling.

641
00:49:11.680 --> 00:49:14.440
and we saw
people being tipped out into the water.

642
00:49:27.080 --> 00:49:28.160
Help me!

643
00:49:31.960 --> 00:49:34.200
On the open area that we're in.

644
00:49:34.280 --> 00:49:36.080
there's a set of double doors.

645
00:49:36.160 --> 00:49:39.240
and behind that is a horizontal corridor.

646
00:49:39.320 --> 00:49:40.720
and it's very wide.

647
00:49:40.800 --> 00:49:43.920
And the other side of it is a… a railing.

648
00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:49.000
but because we were tipping so much.
it was becoming impassable.

649
00:49:49.920 --> 00:49:54.320
We have to get across this chasm.
and we need to get to a lifeboat.

650
00:49:54.400 --> 00:49:57.200
or we at least need to jump in the water.

651
00:49:59.760 --> 00:50:02.320
I yelled out to all the crew members.

652
00:50:02.400 --> 00:50:06.280
what we're gonna do is
we're gonna throw people across the way

653
00:50:06.360 --> 00:50:08.880
so that they can catch on to the banister

654
00:50:08.960 --> 00:50:11.120
and then climb down
to the side of the ship

655
00:50:11.200 --> 00:50:13.640
that was closer to the water.

656
00:50:14.240 --> 00:50:17.400
I'm standing on one side.
I've got a man standing on the other side.

657
00:50:17.480 --> 00:50:20.280
and we're taking people under the arms.
and we're just throwing them.

658
00:50:23.560 --> 00:50:26.920
After we managed to get everyone across.

659
00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:31.000
there were five of us
that. um. at that point. got stranded.

660
00:50:31.760 --> 00:50:36.640
We had tilted so high
that now this was truly an elevator shaft.

661
00:50:36.720 --> 00:50:39.040
There's no way we could've made it across.

662
00:50:41.400 --> 00:50:45.000
At this point.
everything went eerily peaceful.

663
00:50:45.600 --> 00:50:48.880
and it felt like being marooned
on a desert island.

664
00:50:58.480 --> 00:51:00.440
We've gotta get out of the lifeboat.

665
00:51:02.200 --> 00:51:06.040
There was a hatch that wasn't too far
from us that was open

666
00:51:06.120 --> 00:51:08.880
where that was the clear escape point.

667
00:51:08.960 --> 00:51:12.200
The few of us who were not in the pile
at the bottom of it

668
00:51:12.280 --> 00:51:15.600
basically began to try to climb out
through that hatch.

669
00:51:17.120 --> 00:51:19.600
One by one. we climbed our way out.

670
00:51:20.920 --> 00:51:26.120
Then once on the top of the lifeboat.
you then had to get onto the cruise ship.

671
00:51:26.200 --> 00:51:28.480
which was now above us. and we…

672
00:51:28.560 --> 00:51:31.000
There was a gap that we had to clear.

673
00:51:32.120 --> 00:51:34.120
We had to make a human chain.

674
00:51:34.200 --> 00:51:36.440
but there was no way
I could actually climb out

675
00:51:36.520 --> 00:51:38.200
while carrying Lila.

676
00:51:39.040 --> 00:51:41.120
I had to hand Lila to a stranger.

677
00:51:41.640 --> 00:51:44.000
Dangling over the Mediterranean
in the dark.

678
00:51:45.600 --> 00:51:48.240
You know. one slip
and you're down in the water.

679
00:51:48.320 --> 00:51:51.200
which was. you know. who knows
how far below us at that point.

680
00:51:53.160 --> 00:51:54.800
I've always had a fear of heights.

681
00:51:54.880 --> 00:51:57.320
so the notion that I would be
climbing up the side of a ship.

682
00:51:57.400 --> 00:52:00.840
like. by my fingertips.
probably six stories up.

683
00:52:00.920 --> 00:52:03.280
in the dark
over the Med is. like. crazy to me.

684
00:52:05.800 --> 00:52:08.480
But it was the only way Lila or I
or Meghan were getting off.

685
00:52:12.240 --> 00:52:14.760
Then we eventually had to get back
on the ship.

686
00:52:16.040 --> 00:52:18.280
which was a real dark spot
in the night for us.

687
00:52:23.520 --> 00:52:26.560
Our first thought was.
"Is there another lifeboat?"

688
00:52:27.080 --> 00:52:32.240
But it was very quickly evident
that there were no lifeboats left.

689
00:52:35.800 --> 00:52:39.720
I was saying to John.
"Let's swim. We can survive this."

690
00:52:41.440 --> 00:52:45.320
We started talking really seriously
about what it would actually involve.

691
00:52:45.920 --> 00:52:47.640
The height of the jump.

692
00:52:48.400 --> 00:52:50.680
Could Lila survive that jump?

693
00:52:51.720 --> 00:52:55.760
Can we swim with Lila
in the temperature of the water?

694
00:52:56.800 --> 00:52:59.040
So we were weighing
the likelihood of surviving it

695
00:52:59.120 --> 00:53:01.280
against staying on the ship.

696
00:53:03.040 --> 00:53:07.240
That was the time where a different level
of realization began to sink in

697
00:53:07.320 --> 00:53:09.480
that we may not be getting off this boat.

698
00:53:12.760 --> 00:53:15.560
As a Christian.
we're told to not bargain with God.

699
00:53:15.640 --> 00:53:18.480
But that's where your head goes.

700
00:53:19.520 --> 00:53:23.000
And I said.
"God. you just get me off this ship.

701
00:53:23.080 --> 00:53:27.840
I will… show Lila who Jesus is.
I will raise this kid right.

702
00:53:28.480 --> 00:53:30.480
but you've got to get us off this ship."

703
00:53:35.080 --> 00:53:38.800
With the ship being so far tilted over.
we were at the high side.

704
00:53:42.520 --> 00:53:45.200
Then I see what looked like a crew member.

705
00:53:45.280 --> 00:53:46.560
He was dressed in white.

706
00:53:46.640 --> 00:53:50.240
He looked official
in some sort of a uniform. and…

707
00:53:50.320 --> 00:53:53.000
He looked at Lila. He looked at us.

708
00:53:54.800 --> 00:53:57.680
He said. "Get down to this level
on the other side of the ship."

709
00:53:57.760 --> 00:54:00.080
"You all probably are gonna need to swim."

710
00:54:01.120 --> 00:54:03.520
"That's where you're gonna have
the best chance to survive."

711
00:54:06.480 --> 00:54:08.680
I look towards the front of the ship

712
00:54:08.760 --> 00:54:11.280
and see a small group
of passengers standing still.

713
00:54:11.360 --> 00:54:14.240
And I thought. "Are they in trouble?"

714
00:54:14.320 --> 00:54:17.080
"Why haven't they joined all of us?"

715
00:54:17.160 --> 00:54:18.680
Walking towards this small group.

716
00:54:18.760 --> 00:54:22.000
it was very difficult to tell the wall
from the floor.

717
00:54:22.080 --> 00:54:24.920
so I was forced to walk on the walls
at this point.

718
00:54:25.920 --> 00:54:31.920
At first. I checked if the doors
could hold my weight. using my foot.

719
00:54:32.640 --> 00:54:37.400
But then. unfortunately.
one of the doors opened like a hatch.

720
00:54:41.560 --> 00:54:43.880
I fell into the empty darkness

721
00:54:44.640 --> 00:54:46.720
and passed out.

722
00:54:56.520 --> 00:54:58.760
When we got to the island.

723
00:54:59.360 --> 00:55:00.920
what are we supposed to do now?

724
00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:02.120
Where do we go?

725
00:55:02.200 --> 00:55:06.880
There was nobody giving direction
to anyone.

726
00:55:08.120 --> 00:55:11.560
At one point. I screamed.

727
00:55:11.640 --> 00:55:15.080
"Is there anybody that can help us?"

728
00:55:18.800 --> 00:55:23.240
And faintly. I heard someone say.
"Go to the church!"

729
00:55:25.760 --> 00:55:29.160
The first thing I did
was to call my mother.

730
00:55:29.720 --> 00:55:32.760
but the phone didn't ring anymore.

731
00:55:33.640 --> 00:55:38.880
But she said she was on a lifeboat.
so she have to be here somewhere.

732
00:55:40.360 --> 00:55:43.920
We began to search for her and Luisa.

733
00:55:46.640 --> 00:55:49.080
The island was very crowded.

734
00:55:49.600 --> 00:55:53.640
and it seemed impossible to find someone.

735
00:55:54.160 --> 00:55:56.600
We entered every shop.

736
00:55:56.680 --> 00:55:58.720
We entered the church.

737
00:56:01.200 --> 00:56:05.480
The crew still does not know
anything. and the ship is still sinking.

738
00:56:06.120 --> 00:56:08.280
They don't know if anyone's still on it.

739
00:56:09.360 --> 00:56:13.200
We found a little nook in the church.

740
00:56:13.280 --> 00:56:17.640
Everyone's been really anxious
and very scared and cold.

741
00:56:18.160 --> 00:56:20.280
I went and found those foil blankets.

742
00:56:20.360 --> 00:56:22.560
I was able to bring 'em back
to the church.

743
00:56:23.200 --> 00:56:28.840
I can still remember people calling out
their family's name and no reply.

744
00:56:29.840 --> 00:56:31.040
Judy!

745
00:56:32.640 --> 00:56:34.920
Steve! Steve!

746
00:56:35.960 --> 00:56:37.200
Kathy!

747
00:56:40.120 --> 00:56:42.800
We looked everywhere for my mother.

748
00:56:42.880 --> 00:56:48.600
and finally. I just stand near some people

749
00:56:49.600 --> 00:56:51.200
who were watching the ship

750
00:56:51.280 --> 00:56:56.200
because I thought
maybe her lifeboat isn't arrived yet.

751
00:56:59.280 --> 00:57:01.440
As the time passes.

752
00:57:01.960 --> 00:57:07.280
we noticed that the ship
was tilting even more.

753
00:57:07.800 --> 00:57:11.640
This is straight out
of a scene of <i>Titanic</i>. Completely.

754
00:57:13.200 --> 00:57:19.160
To see it from that viewpoint
was so scary.

755
00:57:19.240 --> 00:57:22.680
Yeah. you could see
people on the boat waving their hands.

756
00:57:22.760 --> 00:57:25.040
ask… like…
You could see 'em begging for help.

757
00:57:30.360 --> 00:57:31.760
It was horrible to see it.

758
00:57:31.840 --> 00:57:33.920
Even though you knew you were safe.

759
00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:37.520
you knew that there was
still people trapped on the ship.

760
00:57:44.000 --> 00:57:46.200
We could see there was an open hallway

761
00:57:46.280 --> 00:57:48.840
that went all the way through the ship
to the opposite railing.

762
00:57:48.920 --> 00:57:53.240
and that was going to be the obvious way
for us to get to the other side.

763
00:57:54.600 --> 00:57:58.800
So that cross hallway was
effectively. you know. a 200-foot slide.

764
00:57:59.480 --> 00:58:03.080
So we knew
that once we were on our bottoms.

765
00:58:03.160 --> 00:58:04.880
we could not get back onto our feet.

766
00:58:07.800 --> 00:58:11.640
The boat was still moving so much that
every. you know. half a degree it moved.

767
00:58:11.720 --> 00:58:15.360
a new piece of furniture would just go
barreling down the hallway.

768
00:58:17.200 --> 00:58:21.400
I had Lila still strapped to me.
and I sort of held her on my chest…

769
00:58:23.320 --> 00:58:25.120
…and just slid down that whole thing.

770
00:58:27.200 --> 00:58:29.560
You're tumbling very awkwardly.

771
00:58:29.640 --> 00:58:32.200
barreling down this cross section
on our backs.

772
00:58:35.040 --> 00:58:37.080
Furniture and just stuff all around us.

773
00:58:37.160 --> 00:58:39.680
I mean. we had to be going
20 miles an hour.

774
00:58:41.640 --> 00:58:44.880
I remember feeling a jolt.
Lila's just slammed her head.

775
00:58:50.480 --> 00:58:52.680
Oh my goodness.
she just hit her head so hard.

776
00:58:52.760 --> 00:58:54.040
"Is she okay?"

777
00:58:54.120 --> 00:58:57.160
I mean. I thought for sure
she wouldn't be able to survive that.

778
00:58:58.400 --> 00:59:03.920
I remember him telling me
when we got to the bottom of the slide.

779
00:59:04.600 --> 00:59:06.320
in a… almost like a confession.

780
00:59:06.400 --> 00:59:08.600
"Lila hit her head very hard."

781
00:59:09.120 --> 00:59:11.440
And I could remember the pain in his face.

782
00:59:14.880 --> 00:59:17.160
I think that my reaction
was just to check on her

783
00:59:17.240 --> 00:59:18.360
and that she was crying.

784
00:59:18.440 --> 00:59:21.320
and it was just more of like
a. "She's okay. Let's keep moving."

785
00:59:29.920 --> 00:59:35.960
Once I woke up. I quickly checked myself.

786
00:59:36.040 --> 00:59:38.720
and I realized that I had a broken leg.

787
00:59:39.320 --> 00:59:42.520
Looking around.
I understood that I was in the restaurant.

788
00:59:43.040 --> 00:59:46.600
I started to shout. "Help. help. help!"

789
00:59:46.680 --> 00:59:49.680
But obviously nobody could hear me.

790
00:59:49.760 --> 00:59:52.040
Next to me. there was a frying pan.

791
00:59:52.560 --> 00:59:55.960
I grabbed this pan
and tried to bang it on the ground.

792
01:00:00.640 --> 01:00:02.960
Whilst we're marooned on this doorway.

793
01:00:03.040 --> 01:00:05.560
Deck 5. I could hear knocking.

794
01:00:07.360 --> 01:00:10.520
And it wasn't like. um…
a mechanical kind of knocking.

795
01:00:10.600 --> 01:00:12.040
It was almost like. you know.

796
01:00:12.120 --> 01:00:15.360
like people were trying to let us know
where they were.

797
01:00:15.440 --> 01:00:18.120
But there's no way. like…
We couldn't get to them.

798
01:00:22.640 --> 01:00:26.760
Once we got to the low side.
we could see the water.

799
01:00:29.600 --> 01:00:31.480
Finally. we are this close.

800
01:00:33.720 --> 01:00:37.880
We were trying to get the attention
of whatever lifeboats could maybe hear us.

801
01:00:37.960 --> 01:00:39.320
Hey!

802
01:00:39.400 --> 01:00:43.640
I could see
a lifeboat with people's faces.

803
01:00:44.800 --> 01:00:46.520
I made eye contact with a woman.

804
01:00:46.600 --> 01:00:50.520
and we just sort of locked eyes
for probably just a moment.

805
01:00:51.520 --> 01:00:56.000
I held up Lila and said.
"Bambino." you know. "Take my baby."

806
01:01:00.160 --> 01:01:03.360
And she just… shook her head.

807
01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:08.440
I think she wishes she could help
but couldn't.

808
01:01:10.120 --> 01:01:13.520
At this point.
I was completely broken psychologically.

809
01:01:15.480 --> 01:01:18.440
In my head. I prayed a lot.

810
01:01:30.560 --> 01:01:34.440
But all of a sudden. we noticed
that there was a couple of lifeboats empty

811
01:01:34.520 --> 01:01:37.200
and kind of lingering around the boat.

812
01:01:37.880 --> 01:01:39.320
We saw signs of life.

813
01:01:39.840 --> 01:01:42.720
We both jumped into action. thinking.
"Oh my gosh. are the…

814
01:01:42.800 --> 01:01:45.240
are the lifeboats coming back
for more people?"

815
01:01:47.320 --> 01:01:52.240
And when we did get the attention
of the captain of the lifeboat.

816
01:01:53.000 --> 01:01:56.360
he was trying to get to the opening
where we were standing.

817
01:01:56.880 --> 01:02:00.480
It felt like we were on that deck
waiting what seemed like forever.

818
01:02:01.400 --> 01:02:06.000
During this whole time. the ship continued
to slowly tip further and further.

819
01:02:06.080 --> 01:02:08.680
We just felt like
every minute could be our last.

820
01:02:09.200 --> 01:02:12.640
The lifeboats themselves
are probably ten or 15 feet below us.

821
01:02:12.720 --> 01:02:14.040
The ocean was very rough.

822
01:02:14.120 --> 01:02:16.680
so the boat's sort of banging
against the cruise ship.

823
01:02:17.680 --> 01:02:21.120
And so even the process of being able
to get onto the lifeboat was a risk.

824
01:02:22.400 --> 01:02:25.200
But somehow.
we climbed our way onto the boat.

825
01:02:26.200 --> 01:02:27.640
We're so relieved.

826
01:02:28.960 --> 01:02:30.520
We drove right out from under it.

827
01:02:30.600 --> 01:02:34.080
I mean. and you look up
out the opening of the lifeboat.

828
01:02:34.160 --> 01:02:36.320
and we literally couldn't see sky.

829
01:02:37.880 --> 01:02:40.800
The entire sky is
the side of the cruise ship.

830
01:02:45.320 --> 01:02:46.840
Lila had quieted.

831
01:02:48.160 --> 01:02:54.280
I remember holding her in my arms.
and I was hoping that she's okay.

832
01:02:54.360 --> 01:02:55.720
that nothing was wrong.

833
01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:05.960
I definitely felt like I'm all alone.
Nobody's coming to rescue us.

834
01:03:09.160 --> 01:03:12.200
Then we started hearing
helicopters going overhead.

835
01:03:13.040 --> 01:03:15.800
But the ship was covering us
like an umbrella.

836
01:03:16.920 --> 01:03:18.320
They can't see us.

837
01:03:21.440 --> 01:03:25.520
I couldn't get down to the water level.
I couldn't get back inside the ship.

838
01:03:25.600 --> 01:03:27.080
At this point. we were sinking.

839
01:03:28.320 --> 01:03:29.960
And that was the moment

840
01:03:30.040 --> 01:03:34.320
when this little reel of my life
started playing in front of my eyes.

841
01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:45.120
I remember my dad saying that

842
01:03:46.680 --> 01:03:49.640
it shouldn't be
that children die before parents.

843
01:04:03.160 --> 01:04:07.360
So it was at that mo… moment
that that fight kicked in.

844
01:04:08.440 --> 01:04:10.560
I have to figure out how to survive.

845
01:04:14.360 --> 01:04:17.240
At that point.
I think. "How can they see us?"

846
01:04:18.760 --> 01:04:22.680
And then I realized
I have this flashlight in my pocket.

847
01:04:23.440 --> 01:04:24.640
I don't know Morse code.

848
01:04:24.720 --> 01:04:28.160
but I started flashing the light
to the boat in front of us.

849
01:04:31.800 --> 01:04:34.480
<i>Rescue India Mike Alpha.</i>
<i>Rescue India Mike Alpha.</i>

850
01:04:34.560 --> 01:04:36.440
<i>Go ahead. go ahead.</i>

851
01:04:36.520 --> 01:04:40.720
<i>We have a signal from someone.</i>
<i>We're going to assist them.</i>

852
01:04:41.240 --> 01:04:42.440
<i>Okay. perfect.</i>

853
01:04:43.880 --> 01:04:48.240
And then.
all of a sudden. this man floats down

854
01:04:48.320 --> 01:04:49.600
like James Bond.

855
01:04:54.240 --> 01:04:56.720
We're pulled up into the helicopter.

856
01:04:56.800 --> 01:04:57.920
and one at a time.

857
01:04:58.000 --> 01:05:00.120
they went back down
and got the other four.

858
01:05:02.600 --> 01:05:06.480
<i>All right. well done.</i>
<i>Received three people in good condition</i>

859
01:05:06.560 --> 01:05:08.840
<i>who will be taken to Grosseto Airport.</i>

860
01:05:08.920 --> 01:05:12.480
<i>where people are waiting for first aid.</i>

861
01:05:21.200 --> 01:05:26.000
When I flew away.
I could see everything that I loved

862
01:05:26.080 --> 01:05:28.960
and everything that was my reality
was gone.

863
01:05:30.040 --> 01:05:31.640
But I was alive.

864
01:05:39.480 --> 01:05:42.080
It was late on a Friday night.

865
01:05:42.160 --> 01:05:46.440
My feed was lit up from passengers
who were on some cruise ship

866
01:05:46.520 --> 01:05:49.400
off the coast of Tuscany on Giglio Island.

867
01:05:50.960 --> 01:05:54.160
I knew the only way to find out
what was really going on

868
01:05:54.760 --> 01:05:56.160
was to go there.

869
01:06:01.160 --> 01:06:04.800
<i>It's a crowded cruise ship</i>
<i>that ran aground and is tipped over.</i>

870
01:06:04.880 --> 01:06:07.840
<i>…passengers described</i>
<i>as scenes from the movie </i>Titanic<i>.</i>

871
01:06:07.920 --> 01:06:10.720
<i>As many as 70 people may be missing.</i>

872
01:06:11.440 --> 01:06:13.880
I arrived in Giglio the following day.

873
01:06:13.960 --> 01:06:16.440
about. I wanna say. 6:30 a.m.

874
01:06:17.920 --> 01:06:21.440
I will never forget
seeing the Costa Concordia.

875
01:06:21.520 --> 01:06:26.520
It was difficult not to just stare
at this gigantic boulder

876
01:06:26.600 --> 01:06:28.840
protruding out of the bottom of it.

877
01:06:31.320 --> 01:06:34.760
My job is to try to explain
how on earth this happened.

878
01:06:37.560 --> 01:06:41.320
An Italian cruise ship ran aground
off the coast of Tuscany last night.

879
01:06:41.400 --> 01:06:43.400
Let's be honest. you have thought about it

880
01:06:43.480 --> 01:06:45.800
every time you get on a plane
or a cruise ship.

881
01:06:45.880 --> 01:06:47.880
What happens if something goes wrong?

882
01:06:47.960 --> 01:06:49.160
Well. it happened.

883
01:06:50.600 --> 01:06:52.760
<i>The ship is now in very shallow water.</i>

884
01:06:52.840 --> 01:06:54.800
<i>but it is because of the size of the ship</i>

885
01:06:54.880 --> 01:06:58.640
<i>and the placement of it</i>
<i>in this very rocky area</i>

886
01:06:58.720 --> 01:07:02.120
<i>that they have several dozen</i>
<i>Italian coast-guard divers</i>

887
01:07:02.200 --> 01:07:05.640
<i>who are checking out the perimeter</i>
<i>and inside the ship right now</i>

888
01:07:05.720 --> 01:07:07.960
<i>to see if they can find anyone there.</i>

889
01:07:10.480 --> 01:07:13.200
I am a fire department diver

890
01:07:13.280 --> 01:07:17.440
who specializes in cave diving.

891
01:07:19.400 --> 01:07:21.840
Two single dives. 40 minutes each.

892
01:07:21.920 --> 01:07:25.120
Total duration for the operation.
two hours.

893
01:07:27.280 --> 01:07:29.440
It was my mother's birthday.

894
01:07:29.520 --> 01:07:34.800
and I thought
that I should be at the restaurant.

895
01:07:35.880 --> 01:07:38.120
singing her "Happy Birthday."

896
01:07:39.160 --> 01:07:41.880
but now I am on Giglio Island.

897
01:07:41.960 --> 01:07:43.280
sitting on the ground.

898
01:07:44.080 --> 01:07:46.520
just wondering. "Where is she?"

899
01:07:48.360 --> 01:07:55.000
And I asked myself.
"Will I ever see her again?"

900
01:07:57.600 --> 01:08:00.320
As the time ticked on
and the water was cold.

901
01:08:00.400 --> 01:08:03.360
you know. this is January.
the chance of survival

902
01:08:03.440 --> 01:08:06.160
for anyone after the first 24 hours

903
01:08:06.240 --> 01:08:07.800
ob… obviously diminishes.

904
01:08:08.800 --> 01:08:09.840
Okay.

905
01:08:10.360 --> 01:08:11.720
Detach.

906
01:08:12.840 --> 01:08:14.040
All right!

907
01:08:22.720 --> 01:08:24.880
The fear is huge

908
01:08:25.399 --> 01:08:30.800
because there really was a risk
of ending up at the bottom of the sea

909
01:08:30.880 --> 01:08:37.840
inside this gigantic ship
and becoming victims instead of rescuers.

910
01:08:39.439 --> 01:08:42.399
Everything
that wasn't attached became an obstacle.

911
01:08:43.439 --> 01:08:45.319
There were wires.

912
01:08:45.399 --> 01:08:47.640
There were sharp edges.

913
01:08:47.720 --> 01:08:50.760
All of these things. obviously.
for a diver. puts them at risk.

914
01:08:59.960 --> 01:09:03.520
Dawn finally came. and with it. light.

915
01:09:04.399 --> 01:09:06.520
I was still in this restaurant.

916
01:09:07.319 --> 01:09:10.040
Hours go by. and hypothermia comes.

917
01:09:11.120 --> 01:09:14.640
Having to spend another night
in those conditions. honestly.

918
01:09:15.160 --> 01:09:18.640
I couldn't be sure
I would survive until the next morning.

919
01:09:25.160 --> 01:09:28.240
I started to think that. uh…

920
01:09:28.319 --> 01:09:33.800
if I could… if I could get out
of this situation…

921
01:09:36.479 --> 01:09:39.479
I could start
thinking about having a family.

922
01:09:42.279 --> 01:09:49.240
Um… that was perhaps
what was missing in my life.

923
01:09:55.440 --> 01:09:59.320
We hadn't slept for 48 hours.

924
01:10:00.520 --> 01:10:02.840
The van door opens.

925
01:10:02.920 --> 01:10:06.840
and my boss says.
"There's one more to save. We have to go."

926
01:10:10.040 --> 01:10:12.680
The hotel manager. Manrico Giampedroni.

927
01:10:12.760 --> 01:10:15.480
who was last seen
by several of the witnesses

928
01:10:15.560 --> 01:10:19.960
trying to save people
in the hospitality area of the ship.

929
01:10:21.480 --> 01:10:24.600

930
01:10:27.640 --> 01:10:31.480
calling out for any survivors.

931
01:10:31.560 --> 01:10:34.840
"We are the fire department!
We are the fire department!"

932
01:10:34.920 --> 01:10:36.240
"Is anyone there?"

933
01:10:39.320 --> 01:10:43.160
"Is there someone there?
Can anyone hear me?"

934
01:10:44.840 --> 01:10:46.640
And. at a certain point.

935
01:10:47.160 --> 01:10:48.880
there was a response.

936
01:10:52.040 --> 01:10:55.400
<i>All right. calm down. Take it easy.</i>

937
01:10:56.200 --> 01:11:02.960
We had squeezed
into the bowels of the tunnel.

938
01:11:03.040 --> 01:11:08.800
so we didn't have natural lighting.

939
01:11:08.880 --> 01:11:10.760
The light could not reach there.

940
01:11:10.840 --> 01:11:13.120
We were. like. inside a cave.

941
01:11:15.520 --> 01:11:17.360
<i>Okay. that's fine. Slowly.</i>

942
01:11:18.800 --> 01:11:20.400
<i>Slowly. That's fine.</i>

943
01:11:21.240 --> 01:11:22.320
<i>Slowly.</i>

944
01:11:23.680 --> 01:11:24.680
<i>Slowly.</i>

945
01:11:26.960 --> 01:11:28.120
<i>That's right!</i>

946
01:11:33.280 --> 01:11:38.120
And then I see
the person we're looking for.

947
01:11:39.960 --> 01:11:43.480
"Hi. what's your name?
What's your name?" I ask.

948
01:11:43.560 --> 01:11:46.360
And he answers me. "Manrico."

949
01:11:46.440 --> 01:11:48.200
"Manrico Giampedroni."

950
01:11:50.440 --> 01:11:53.000
He tells me. "Hi. I'm Francesco…

951
01:11:57.320 --> 01:11:59.160
one of your rescuers."

952
01:11:59.680 --> 01:12:01.680
He tells me. "Don't worry now."

953
01:12:04.600 --> 01:12:06.000
"We'll get you out."

954
01:12:17.760 --> 01:12:20.560
After 13 years. I still cry.

955
01:12:21.600 --> 01:12:22.880
It's unbelievable.

956
01:12:27.960 --> 01:12:31.240
<i>Always something</i>
<i>akin to a miracle in disasters.</i>

957
01:12:31.320 --> 01:12:33.840
<i>This time.</i>
<i>it was a crewman trapped inside.</i>

958
01:12:33.920 --> 01:12:37.760
<i>found by rescuers going cabin to cabin</i>
<i>and tapping on the hull.</i>

959
01:12:37.840 --> 01:12:40.720
<i>Two days trapped with a broken leg.</i>

960
01:12:41.760 --> 01:12:43.800
Did you think you might not make it?

961
01:12:43.880 --> 01:12:49.400
Yes. when I was alone
in the restaurant. yes.

962
01:12:54.560 --> 01:12:58.120
<i>After the shock. the panic. the chaos.</i>

963
01:12:58.200 --> 01:13:00.240
<i>tears of relief.</i>

964
01:13:00.920 --> 01:13:05.960
<i>Dancer Rose Metcalf was one of the last</i>
<i>to be rescued from the sinking ship.</i>

965
01:13:06.480 --> 01:13:10.920
<i>Others. including Nick Tally</i>
<i>and his friends. are also safe.</i>

966
01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:13.800
There was families trembling.
handing me their children.

967
01:13:13.880 --> 01:13:17.480
telling me. you know.
"Take my child. Put him on the boat."

968
01:13:17.560 --> 01:13:21.280
And we had to wait over an hour and a half
before we could get onto that boat.

969
01:13:31.200 --> 01:13:34.320
I had to wait two years.

970
01:13:35.680 --> 01:13:40.720
My mother's body was
one of the last ones to be found.

971
01:13:44.880 --> 01:13:47.480
Finding her body

972
01:13:48.320 --> 01:13:50.520
wasn't comforting for me at all.

973
01:13:52.840 --> 01:13:58.000
It's like
Costa Concordia interrupted my life.

974
01:13:58.920 --> 01:14:03.840
She was my entire world.

975
01:14:04.560 --> 01:14:05.680
and I was hers.

976
01:14:07.040 --> 01:14:09.600
What's the name of this beautiful child?

977
01:14:09.680 --> 01:14:12.520
This girl is called Stefania.

978
01:14:12.600 --> 01:14:14.360
Whose is this child?

979
01:14:20.080 --> 01:14:23.240
The captain
of the cruise ship that ran aground here

980
01:14:23.320 --> 01:14:24.720
on the coast of Tuscany

981
01:14:24.800 --> 01:14:26.760
has been stopped
by the Italian authorities.

982
01:14:26.840 --> 01:14:30.440
He's being investigated for manslaughter
and for abandoning ship.

983
01:14:30.520 --> 01:14:34.000
These are two very serious offenses
in maritime law.

984
01:14:34.080 --> 01:14:38.040
Thirty-two people died that night.
including a 5-year-old child.

985
01:14:39.520 --> 01:14:41.320
In the days after the accident.

986
01:14:41.400 --> 01:14:45.320
the Costa PR team was really
the only conduit for the information.

987
01:14:46.160 --> 01:14:50.080
and it was very clear they had
already decided whose fault it was.

988
01:14:50.160 --> 01:14:52.680
And tonight.
the blame game has stepped up a gear

989
01:14:52.760 --> 01:14:56.120
with the ship's owners saying
that their captain was at fault.

990
01:14:56.200 --> 01:15:00.200
We believe it has been
a… a human error here.

991
01:15:00.280 --> 01:15:04.080
The captain did not follow
the authorized route.

992
01:15:05.920 --> 01:15:07.920
Captain. Captain!

993
01:15:09.360 --> 01:15:12.000
One
of the most dramatic aspects of the story

994
01:15:12.080 --> 01:15:15.280
happened on 17th January.

995
01:15:15.360 --> 01:15:20.760
A local journalist found a USB key
in his unlocked vehicle.

996
01:15:21.280 --> 01:15:24.760
This USB contained
an intercept of a conversation

997
01:15:24.840 --> 01:15:28.560
between the coast guard in Livorno
and Captain Schettino

998
01:15:28.640 --> 01:15:32.720
in the period of time
after Schettino said he had left the ship.

999
01:15:32.800 --> 01:15:34.840

1000
01:15:34.920 --> 01:15:38.320
<i>I am here to coordinate the rescue.</i>

1001
01:15:38.400 --> 01:15:43.040
<i>Coordinate the rescue</i>
<i>from on board. Are you refusing?</i>

1002
01:15:43.560 --> 01:15:45.320
<i>No. no. I'm not refusing.</i>

1003
01:15:45.400 --> 01:15:47.880
<i>Are you refusing to go on board. Captain?</i>

1004
01:15:47.960 --> 01:15:50.200
<i>Tell me. why are you not going on board?</i>

1005
01:15:50.280 --> 01:15:52.320
Once you heard this commander saying

1006
01:15:52.400 --> 01:15:55.080
to Captain Schettino.
"Get back on the… on the ship."

1007
01:15:55.160 --> 01:15:56.240
you couldn't unhear it.

1008
01:15:56.320 --> 01:15:58.640

1009
01:15:58.720 --> 01:16:01.520
<i>You must not make any other assessment.</i>
<i>You have declared abandon ship.</i>

1010
01:16:01.600 --> 01:16:03.080
<i>Now I am in charge!</i>

1011
01:16:03.160 --> 01:16:04.560
<i>Go back on board!</i>

1012
01:16:05.760 --> 01:16:08.800
<i>Is that clear? Can you not hear me?</i>

1013
01:16:08.880 --> 01:16:11.040
-<i>I am going back on board.</i>
-<i>Go!</i>

1014
01:16:11.560 --> 01:16:14.280
The inarguable result
of that was that anyone.

1015
01:16:14.360 --> 01:16:17.760
anywhere in the world.
knew Captain Schettino as Captain Coward.

1016
01:16:17.840 --> 01:16:19.280
Can you let me through?

1017
01:16:19.360 --> 01:16:22.640
<i>The Italian captain. Francesco Schettino.</i>

1018
01:16:22.720 --> 01:16:24.400
<i>striding into court this morning</i>

1019
01:16:24.480 --> 01:16:28.120
<i>with that same confident swagger</i>
<i>he displayed aboard his ship.</i>

1020
01:16:28.200 --> 01:16:30.760
Captain Francesco Schettino
was in court today

1021
01:16:30.840 --> 01:16:34.640
to face charges of multiple manslaughter.
causing a maritime disaster.

1022
01:16:34.720 --> 01:16:37.720
and causing personal injury to 150 people.

1023
01:16:37.800 --> 01:16:40.000
The trial lasted for several years.

1024
01:16:40.080 --> 01:16:44.080
and it was held inside of a theater
in the city of Grosseto.

1025
01:16:44.160 --> 01:16:46.640
And I went to every single hearing.

1026
01:16:47.200 --> 01:16:49.840
The prosecution has laid the blame
for the disaster

1027
01:16:49.920 --> 01:16:52.360
very firmly on Captain Schettino.

1028
01:16:52.440 --> 01:16:57.200
It says that in his command of his ship.
he was grossly negligent.

1029
01:16:57.280 --> 01:17:00.720
but the captain denies
all the charges against him.

1030
01:17:00.800 --> 01:17:06.040
and he insists that others must share
responsibility for what happened.

1031
01:17:06.560 --> 01:17:09.800
The entire focus was on Captain Schettino.

1032
01:17:09.880 --> 01:17:13.200
but one of the primary questions
that a lot of us had

1033
01:17:13.280 --> 01:17:17.080
was whether or not this was
some sort of a mechanical failure.

1034
01:17:18.320 --> 01:17:21.600
Shortly after the accident.
the black box was recovered.

1035
01:17:21.680 --> 01:17:23.160
but it was faulty.

1036
01:17:23.240 --> 01:17:25.200
and so it seemed for a period of time

1037
01:17:25.280 --> 01:17:27.480
that there would be absolutely no way
to find out

1038
01:17:27.560 --> 01:17:30.680
what was really going on on the bridge
the night of the accident.

1039
01:17:34.840 --> 01:17:37.760
2012. I was
a young computer science researcher.

1040
01:17:41.920 --> 01:17:43.720
I was given a bunch of discs

1041
01:17:43.800 --> 01:17:45.440
from the Costa Concordia.

1042
01:17:45.520 --> 01:17:48.960
Two experts already tried
to take the data out.

1043
01:17:49.840 --> 01:17:51.280
and they both failed.

1044
01:17:51.800 --> 01:17:53.000
So I was obsessed.

1045
01:17:54.960 --> 01:18:00.080
I created a software which describes
everything that happened that night.

1046
01:18:05.760 --> 01:18:07.880
The emergency generator
of the Costa Concordia

1047
01:18:07.960 --> 01:18:09.240
had a problem that night.

1048
01:18:09.760 --> 01:18:13.400
In particular. it powered
on and off several time

1049
01:18:13.480 --> 01:18:19.400
and almost never was able to connect
to the emergency power lines

1050
01:18:19.480 --> 01:18:22.280
and power the emergency devices.

1051
01:18:23.600 --> 01:18:28.280
It's impossible to know with certainty
exactly how people died on the ship.

1052
01:18:28.360 --> 01:18:31.440
but we do know
that at least two of the lifeboats

1053
01:18:31.520 --> 01:18:33.760
on the upper side of the ship failed

1054
01:18:33.840 --> 01:18:36.960
because of
the emergency generator's failure.

1055
01:18:37.040 --> 01:18:39.920
and we know
that those people had to disembark

1056
01:18:40.000 --> 01:18:44.280
and had to try to find their way
to other lifeboats on the same deck. four.

1057
01:18:45.440 --> 01:18:47.000
We also know that… that.

1058
01:18:47.080 --> 01:18:50.040
because of the failure
of the emergency generator.

1059
01:18:50.120 --> 01:18:52.200
the elevators weren't working.

1060
01:19:00.320 --> 01:19:04.120
When running the software
I wrote to put all this data in sync.

1061
01:19:04.200 --> 01:19:05.720
there was one big surprise.

1062
01:19:05.800 --> 01:19:08.440
Immediately before the accident.

1063
01:19:08.520 --> 01:19:13.680
we found out that there was a mismatch
between the order given to the helmsman

1064
01:19:13.760 --> 01:19:15.200
and what he was doing.

1065
01:19:23.240 --> 01:19:26.840
We hear Schettino
giving some instructions.

1066
01:19:26.920 --> 01:19:32.960
and the helmsman. for 13 seconds.
does the exact opposite.

1067
01:19:34.000 --> 01:19:35.880
Later. an independent study

1068
01:19:35.960 --> 01:19:39.840
by Professor Bruno Neri
and Paolo Neri of the University of Pisa

1069
01:19:39.920 --> 01:19:44.040
demonstrated that if Schettino's orders
would have been executed correctly.

1070
01:19:44.120 --> 01:19:48.240
the impact would have been partial
or nonexistent.

1071
01:19:56.360 --> 01:20:00.400
In the early 2000s.
the cruise industry was exploding.

1072
01:20:02.240 --> 01:20:05.960
and the Italian-run
Costa cruise-line company was in trouble.

1073
01:20:06.040 --> 01:20:07.320
They couldn't compete.

1074
01:20:07.400 --> 01:20:10.480
The only way
that they could survive in that market

1075
01:20:10.560 --> 01:20:13.400
was to be acquired
by an American corporation.

1076
01:20:15.560 --> 01:20:18.800
With Costa's expansion.
they had to find staff

1077
01:20:18.880 --> 01:20:22.480
and to try to train them as quickly
and efficiently as possible.

1078
01:20:23.000 --> 01:20:26.280
It's important to note
that Captain Schettino himself

1079
01:20:26.360 --> 01:20:28.640
had written to Costa
and said that he was concerned

1080
01:20:28.720 --> 01:20:30.920
that people were being promoted
too quickly.

1081
01:20:31.000 --> 01:20:32.920
that they weren't being
trained adequately.

1082
01:20:33.000 --> 01:20:36.840
and they just didn't fit in line
with the type of ship he wanted to run.

1083
01:20:38.240 --> 01:20:43.120
What we know about the helmsman is that
he had been promoted quickly to the job.

1084
01:20:43.200 --> 01:20:45.800
and it seems very clear
that at the moment of crisis

1085
01:20:45.880 --> 01:20:50.240
when he was needed very much to understand
the orders from Captain Schettino.

1086
01:20:50.320 --> 01:20:52.440
there was a language barrier.
and it is likely

1087
01:20:52.520 --> 01:20:55.360
that he just didn't understand
what the captain told him to do.

1088
01:21:07.680 --> 01:21:11.160
In the name
of the Italian people. the court.

1089
01:21:11.760 --> 01:21:16.320
in accordance with articles 533 and 535.

1090
01:21:16.840 --> 01:21:19.040
declares Francesco Schettino

1091
01:21:19.120 --> 01:21:21.160
guilty of the crimes attributed to him

1092
01:21:21.240 --> 01:21:27.000
The total sentence of 16 years
of imprisonment and one month of arrest.

1093
01:21:27.080 --> 01:21:29.280
Today. the captain of the Costa Concordia

1094
01:21:29.360 --> 01:21:32.840
was convicted of manslaughter
and abandoning ship

1095
01:21:32.920 --> 01:21:34.560
and sentenced to 16 years.

1096
01:21:49.160 --> 01:21:52.440
I will never work
for the cruise industry ever again.

1097
01:21:54.840 --> 01:21:59.920
And I pray
nobody should face this situation.

1098
01:22:02.280 --> 01:22:03.280
All my money.

1099
01:22:03.960 --> 01:22:05.080
I lost it.

1100
01:22:05.160 --> 01:22:09.640
But I learned that life
is more important than money.

1101
01:22:10.960 --> 01:22:13.880
And so every morning when I wake up.

1102
01:22:14.480 --> 01:22:15.960
the first thing I do.

1103
01:22:16.040 --> 01:22:17.800
I say thank you.

1104
01:22:19.960 --> 01:22:21.360
I learnt a lot.

1105
01:22:22.080 --> 01:22:23.760
Now I can swim.

1106
01:22:35.440 --> 01:22:38.200
You wanna sing again? Okay. go ahead.

1107
01:22:39.240 --> 01:22:41.240
Ma-ma-ma.

1108
01:22:42.040 --> 01:22:44.840
Ama-ma-ma-ma!

1109
01:22:45.640 --> 01:22:47.520
Two. three…

1110
01:22:48.960 --> 01:22:52.120
When we got home.
I mean. I was completely broken.

1111
01:22:53.640 --> 01:22:58.480
I mean. I was diagnosed with PTSD.
I had panic attacks. I had nightmares.

1112
01:22:59.480 --> 01:23:02.200
We were worried about Lila

1113
01:23:02.280 --> 01:23:07.080
after all that she had gone through
both physically and emotionally.

1114
01:23:07.800 --> 01:23:11.480
We had to watch her for a couple of weeks
just to make sure everything was fine.

1115
01:23:12.000 --> 01:23:13.760
Oh. look at that tongue.

1116
01:23:14.320 --> 01:23:16.280
What other funny faces can you make?

1117
01:23:17.600 --> 01:23:19.080
I saw what it did to me.

1118
01:23:19.160 --> 01:23:21.480
but this is a one-year-old
that can't communicate.

1119
01:23:21.560 --> 01:23:26.320
and so I remember we were talking
to psychologists and specialists.

1120
01:23:26.400 --> 01:23:29.640
See you later. bye! Have fun!

1121
01:23:30.840 --> 01:23:32.600
-Bye-bye.
-Bye-bye.

1122
01:23:33.120 --> 01:23:38.680
But she turned out to have
a perfectly normal childhood.

1123
01:23:39.520 --> 01:23:41.120
So we… we talk about it often.

1124
01:23:41.200 --> 01:23:45.640
It's like.
why did God choose to save us that night?

1125
01:23:45.720 --> 01:23:47.080
You know. why are we here?

1126
01:23:47.160 --> 01:23:50.320
What is it that we should be doing
with the time he's given us?

1127
01:23:50.400 --> 01:23:53.600
Lila has her life.
the beautiful life she's lived.

1128
01:23:54.200 --> 01:23:57.600
And. by God's grace. uh… we survived.

1129
01:23:59.440 --> 01:24:01.760
John. she survived because of you.

1130
01:24:19.600 --> 01:24:23.720
I just fought so hard that night
to try to save them.

1131
01:24:24.880 --> 01:24:27.120
There were times
I didn't think we were gonna get off.

1132
01:24:28.280 --> 01:24:29.960
But I'm so glad we did.

1133
01:24:31.880 --> 01:24:34.800
I just look back. what the last decade
or so has been like.

1134
01:24:35.320 --> 01:24:38.120
like the lives we've been able to live.
we feel so fortunate for.

1135
01:24:40.280 --> 01:24:45.920
Lila is the most well-rounded.
grounded. incredible 15-year-old.

1136
01:24:47.080 --> 01:24:49.880
And she's the most beautiful ballerina.

1137
01:24:51.320 --> 01:24:54.200
She has this God-given passion for dance.

1138
01:25:01.200 --> 01:25:03.360
She's just such a beautiful young woman.

1139
01:25:04.160 --> 01:25:05.680
The world is her oyster.

1140
01:25:06.360 --> 01:25:08.440
She's gonna have some impact on it

1141
01:25:08.520 --> 01:25:10.920
as a result
of getting off the ship that night.

1142
01:25:24.520 --> 01:25:28.320
We learned very shortly after we got back

1143
01:25:28.840 --> 01:25:30.520
that Meghan was pregnant.

1144
01:25:31.160 --> 01:25:35.360
You know. she was pregnant that night
as we were fighting for our lives.

1145
01:25:36.040 --> 01:25:42.000
One of the greatest gifts I could've
been given was that pregnancy.

1146
01:25:45.080 --> 01:25:49.440
What's funny is my ultrasounds show.
when they timed the baby.

1147
01:25:49.520 --> 01:25:53.760
the… the conception date
was the night of the cruise disaster.

1148
01:25:53.840 --> 01:25:57.120
and we were like. "I can assure you that's
not when he was conceived." but. um…

1149
01:25:58.280 --> 01:26:00.840
Now you know why
I didn't have time to put my shirt on!

